  "shortBio": "Known as the “Moonshoal Glider of Foamcrests,” Tideotter belongs to Moonwater Coast’s living edges. Tideotters move four-footed and sure on uneven ground, stay social with strangers, and lean on slick scales when the air turns strange. They savor Moonvine. In Moonwater Coast, they favor Moonvine and teach quieter routes to those who listen.",
  "standardBio": "Tideotter, titled among keepers as “Moonshoal Glider,” carries shifting memory in every movement. Native to Moonwater Coast, the species ebbs through brine and tideglass, leaving traces that other Riftlings can follow like soft maps. Wild groups form loose bonds rather than rigid packs; a social individual may become the emotional center of a small hearthline. They eat Moonvine eagerly and dislike food that smells of neglect or spoilage. Ancient keepers carved Tideotter silhouettes into travel stones, believing the species guided the lost. Modern hatcheries record them as reliable companions; their practical problem-solving intelligence makes training feel like conversation. Their signature ability, Tideotter's Ray Glide, reflects a life shaped by Moonwater Coast more than by arena ambition. Many assume Tideotters are aggressive because of their tide affinity; most are cautious first. Young Tideotters practice Tideotter's Ray Glide as play long before they understand battle. Adults teach by demonstration: where to rest, what to avoid, how to share warmth or shade.",
  "fullLore": "Tideotters first condensed from residual mooncurrent along the living edges of Moonwater Coast after early Rift fractures cooled into weather. Their eggs appear where brine and tideglass gathers into stillness—never in the loudest danger, always in the pocket of calm beside it. Early surveyors mistook them for ambient phenomena until a Tideotter returned a dropped lantern, carefully, as if returning a promise.\n\nIn ancient eras, regional peoples treated Tideotters as omen-bearers rather than pets. Carvings show them walking ahead of caravans, pausing at unstable ground, and curling around children during ashfall or fog. The species was never “tamed” in the old sense; it chose. That choice culture survives in modern Riftkeeper etiquette: you do not yank a Tideotter into a bond. You invite, wait, and keep the invitation honest.\n\nModern history is quieter and more practical. Hatcheries map Tideotter care cycles with the same seriousness given to rare lines, because common does not mean shallow. Moonwater Coast still holds wild populations that trade soft greetings with passerby pets. After major Rift events, Tideotters often appear first at recovery centers—not as heroes, but as inventory clerks of comfort, counting who is cold, hungry, or afraid.\n\nNatural behavior is social at the core and adaptable at the edges. They are four-footed and sure on uneven ground, companion-sized, easy to cradle, and communicate through tap-codes on stone or wood. Socially, they prefer small trusted circles; strangers are assessed by scent, posture, and whether a keeper’s voice stays kind under stress. Intelligence presents as practical problem-solving intelligence. They sleep in shallow scrapes and prefer weather that matches their affinity’s comfort band.\n\nEcologically, Tideotters act as cleanup foragers within Moonwater Coast. Allies often include Tidewisp and Moonray; rivalries with Riftslug and Dawnkit are usually about nesting space or shiny refuse, not blood feuds. Predators are rare—most threats come from collapsing terrain and careless machines rather than jaws.\n\nCulture around them is affectionate and slightly superstitious. Travelers once claimed that following a wild Tideotter through Moonwater Coast would lead them past a Rift storm unharmed. Collectors prize unusual cosmetics, yet marketplace notes remind buyers that verified care history matters more than glitter. The common misunderstanding remains: Many assume Tideotters are aggressive because of their tide affinity; most are cautious first. The hidden truth keepers debate in soft rooms is simpler and stranger: Their brine and tideglass scent intensifies near forgotten vaults, which may explain keeper superstitions.\n\nFrom egg to evolved form, their life story stays continuous. Eggs look like copper seed-cases veined with tide light. Hatchlings are clumsy with sincerity; adults become specialists of place; evolved stages sharpen instinct without erasing childhood habits. Battle tendencies favor protective bursts, and evolution philosophy insists transformation should answer lived experience—not fashion.\n\nFor Riftkeepers, a Tideotter is a living chapter of Moonwater Coast. Feed it Moonvine, respect its social tempo, and it will teach you the region’s quieter grammar: which winds lie, which stones remember, which silences are safe. Personal quests often begin with a shell symbol, a remembered scent, or a dream of a door that only opens when the bond is honest. That is the Tideotter bargain—not destiny sold at rarity price, but a life that continues because you showed up.",
